{"title_page": "Lutheran Book of Worship", "text_new": "{{short description|Worship book and hymnal used by several Lutheran denominations in North America}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox hymnal\n| name            = '''Lutheran Book of Worship'''\n| cover           = Lutheran Book of Worship.JPG\n| caption         = 1978 edition of the ''Lutheran Book of Worship''\n| commissioned_by =\n| approved_for    =\n| country         = United States\n| pages           =\n| publisher       = [[Augsburg Fortress]]\n| released        = 1978\n| number_of_hymns = 569\n| psalms          = 150\n| service_music   =\n| last_hymnal     = ''[[Service Book and Hymnal]]''\n| next_hymnal     = '''''With One Voice'''''\n}}\n{{Infobox hymnal\n| name            = '''With One Voice'''\n| cover           = With One Voice.JPG\n| caption         = 1995 edition of ''With One Voice''\n| commissioned_by =\n| approved_for    =\n| country         = United States\n| pages           =\n| publisher       = [[Augsburg Fortress]]\n| released        = 1995\n| number_of_hymns = \n| psalms          = \n| service_music   =\n| last_hymnal     = '''''Lutheran Book of Worship'''''\n| next_hymnal     = ''[[Evangelical Lutheran Worship]]''\n}}\n\nThe '''''Lutheran Book of Worship''''' ('''''LBW''''') is a [[worship]] book and [[hymn]]al used by several [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[religious denomination|denominations]] in [[North America]].  A supplement, '''''With One Voice''''' ('''''WOV'''''), contains additional hymns and service music. The ''LBW'' is sometimes called the \"green book\", as opposed to ''With One Voice'', which is bound in blue; or ''[[Service Book and Hymnal]]'', which is bound in red; or ''[[The Lutheran Hymnal]]'', which is also bound in red, with a simple gold cross.\n\n== History ==\nWhen Lutheran churches were first established in North America, the immigrants from [[Germany]], [[Sweden]], [[Norway]], [[Finland]], and other non-English-speaking countries retained services in their native languages. However, as the children and grandchildren of these immigrants began speaking English in their everyday lives and the various Lutheran denominations began uniting, many felt that the North American Lutheran churches needed a common English-language [[liturgy]] and hymns. Although the eighteenth-century missionary [[Henry Melchior Muhlenberg]] had hoped for the day when Lutherans would be \"one church [with] one book\", it was not until the 1888 \"Common Service\" that a majority of English-speaking Lutherans in North America began to use the same texts for worship, albeit with minor adaptations. (Senn, 584-591.) The \"Common Liturgy\" included in the 1958 [[Service Book and Hymnal]] was a major revision of the \"Common Service\", and introduced a Eucharistic Prayer into American Lutheran usage. [[Culto Cristiano]], a 1964 service book, attempted to offer a unified liturgy for Spanish-speaking Lutherans.\n\nThe process leading to the publication of the ''LBW'' was started in 1965 when the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]] (LCMS) invited other North American Lutheran denominations to join it to work on a common service book. Together with the LCMS, the [[Lutheran Church in America]], the [[American Lutheran Church]], and the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in Canada|Evangelical Lutheran Church of Canada]] formed the '''Inter-Lutheran Commission on Worship''' to undertake this project. The commission conducted its work through four sub-committees: Liturgical Text Committee, Liturgical Music Committee, Hymn Text Committee, Hymn Music Committee. The work of the committees was validated via provisional liturgical and hymn materials, questionnaires, conferences, and dialogs. The Rev. Dr. Eugene Brand was named project director for the development work and The Rev. Leonard Flachman was named publishers' representative and managing editor. The ''LBW'' was published in [[1978 in literature|1978]]. The LCMS pulled out of the ILCW just prior to the publication of the ''LBW'', but having been a participant in the development of the materials its name appears on the title page. The LCMS published its own hymnal, ''[[Lutheran Worship]]'' (LW), in 1982.  Although the ''LW'' liturgies are very similar to those in the ''LBW'', there are differences which reflect differing theologies. For example, ''LW'' lacks the option for a Eucharistic Prayer.\n\nThe ''Lutheran Book of Worship'' has remained in use for thirty years. There are a couple reasons for that longevity. The first is the careful, forward-looking, inclusive work of the ILCW and the four subcommittees. The second is the careful work done by the staff of [[Augsburg Fortress|Augsburg Publishing House]] in selecting and testing the materials with which the book was manufactured. The books did not wear out.\n\nThe first printing of the ''LBW'' was one million copies and required 19 semi-trailers to carry the book from the printer to 14 distribution points around the United States.\n\nWhile it is in its twenty-seventh printing and widely used by the ELCA and the ELCIC, the ''LBW'' was replaced in October 2006 as the primary worship resource in the two denominations by ''[[Evangelical Lutheran Worship]]''. The new book is intended to reflect the changing demographic of the church bodies and the subsequent changes in language and ritual practice.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of English-language hymnals by denomination]]\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite book|title=Lutheran Book of Worship|last=|first=|publisher=Augsburg Publishing House and Lutheran Church in America Publication Board|year=1978|isbn=0-8006-3330-X|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=With One Voice|last=|first=|publisher=[[Augsburg Fortress]]|year=1995|isbn=0-8066-0051-9|location=|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/withonevoiceluth00evan}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Christian Liturgy: Catholic and Evangelical|last=Senn|first=Frank C.|publisher=Augsburg Fortress|year=1997|isbn=0-8006-2726-1|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Encountering God: The Legacy of Lutheran Book of Worship|last=|first=|publisher=Kirk House Publishers|year=1998|isbn=1-886513-15-5|editor-last=Van Loon|editor-first=Ralph R.|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=In the Context of Unity: A History of the Development of Lutheran Book of Worship|last=Quere|first=Ralph W.|publisher=Lutheran University Press|year=2003|isbn=1-932688-00-5|location=|pages=}}\n\n{{Lutheran Divine Service}}\n{{Lutheran hymnody}}\n\n[[Category:Lutheran hymnals]]\n[[Category:1978 books]]\n[[Category:Christian prayer books]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian texts]]\n[[Category:1978 in music]]\n[[Category:1978 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]]\n[[Category:Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Worship book and hymnal used by several Lutheran denominations in North America}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox hymnal\n| name            = '''Lutheran Book of Worship'''\n| cover           = Lutheran Book of Worship.JPG\n| caption         = 1978 edition of the ''Lutheran Book of Worship''\n| commissioned_by =\n| approved_for    =\n| country         = United States\n| pages           =\n| publisher       = [[Augsburg Fortress]]\n| released        = 1978\n| number_of_hymns = 569\n| psalms          = 150\n| service_music   =\n| last_hymnal     = ''[[Service Book and Hymnal]]''\n| next_hymnal     = '''''With One Voice'''''\n}}\n{{Infobox hymnal\n| name            = '''With One Voice'''\n| cover           = With One Voice.JPG\n| caption         = 1995 edition of ''With One Voice''\n| commissioned_by =\n| approved_for    =\n| country         = United States\n| pages           =\n| publisher       = [[Augsburg Fortress]]\n| released        = 1995\n| number_of_hymns = \n| psalms          = \n| service_music   =\n| last_hymnal     = '''''Lutheran Book of Worship'''''\n| next_hymnal     = ''[[Evangelical Lutheran Worship]]''\n}}\n\nThe '''''Lutheran Book of Worship''''' ('''''LBW''''') is a [[worship]] book and [[hymn]]al used by several [[Lutheranism|Lutheran]] [[religious denomination|denominations]] in [[North America]].  A supplement, '''''With One Voice''''' ('''''WOV'''''), contains additional hymns and service music. The ''LBW'' is sometimes called the \"green book\", as opposed to ''With One Voice'', which is bound in blue; or ''[[Service Book and Hymnal]]'', which is bound in red; or ''[[The Lutheran Hymnal]]'', which is also bound in red, with a simple gold cross.\n\n== History ==\nWhen Lutheran churches were first established in North America, the immigrants from [[Germany]], [[Sweden]], [[Norway]], [[Finland]], and other non-English-speaking countries retained services in their native languages. However, as the children and grandchildren of these immigrants began speaking English in their everyday lives and the various Lutheran denominations began uniting, many felt that the North American Lutheran churches needed a common English-language [[liturgy]] and hymns. Although the eighteenth-century missionary [[Henry Melchior Muhlenberg]] had hoped for the day when Lutherans would be \"one church [with] one book\", it was not until the 1888 \"Common Service\" that a majority of English-speaking Lutherans in North America began to use the same texts for worship, albeit with minor adaptations. (Senn, 584-591.) The \"Common Liturgy\" included in the 1958 [[Service Book and Hymnal]] was a major revision of the \"Common Service\", and introduced a Eucharistic Prayer into American Lutheran usage. ''Culto Cristiano'', a 1964 service book, attempted to offer a unified liturgy for Spanish-speaking Lutherans.\n\nThe process leading to the publication of the ''LBW'' was started in 1965 when the [[Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]] (LCMS) invited other North American Lutheran denominations to join it to work on a common service book. Together with the LCMS, the [[Lutheran Church in America]], the [[American Lutheran Church]], and the [[Evangelical Lutheran Church in Canada|Evangelical Lutheran Church of Canada]] formed the '''Inter-Lutheran Commission on Worship''' to undertake this project. The commission conducted its work through four sub-committees: Liturgical Text Committee, Liturgical Music Committee, Hymn Text Committee, Hymn Music Committee. The work of the committees was validated via provisional liturgical and hymn materials, questionnaires, conferences, and dialogs. The Rev. Dr. Eugene Brand was named project director for the development work and The Rev. Leonard Flachman was named publishers' representative and managing editor. The ''LBW'' was published in [[1978 in literature|1978]]. The LCMS pulled out of the ILCW just prior to the publication of the ''LBW'', but having been a participant in the development of the materials its name appears on the title page. The LCMS published its own hymnal, ''[[Lutheran Worship]]'' (LW), in 1982.  Although the ''LW'' liturgies are very similar to those in the ''LBW'', there are differences which reflect differing theologies. For example, ''LW'' lacks the option for a Eucharistic Prayer.\n\nThe ''Lutheran Book of Worship'' has remained in use for thirty years. There are a couple reasons for that longevity. The first is the careful, forward-looking, inclusive work of the ILCW and the four subcommittees. The second is the careful work done by the staff of [[Augsburg Fortress|Augsburg Publishing House]] in selecting and testing the materials with which the book was manufactured. The books did not wear out.\n\nThe first printing of the ''LBW'' was one million copies and required 19 semi-trailers to carry the book from the printer to 14 distribution points around the United States.\n\nWhile it is in its twenty-seventh printing and widely used by the ELCA and the ELCIC, the ''LBW'' was replaced in October 2006 as the primary worship resource in the two denominations by ''[[Evangelical Lutheran Worship]]''. The new book is intended to reflect the changing demographic of the church bodies and the subsequent changes in language and ritual practice.\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of English-language hymnals by denomination]]\n\n==References==\n*{{Cite book|title=Lutheran Book of Worship|last=|first=|publisher=Augsburg Publishing House and Lutheran Church in America Publication Board|year=1978|isbn=0-8006-3330-X|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=With One Voice|last=|first=|publisher=[[Augsburg Fortress]]|year=1995|isbn=0-8066-0051-9|location=|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/withonevoiceluth00evan}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Christian Liturgy: Catholic and Evangelical|last=Senn|first=Frank C.|publisher=Augsburg Fortress|year=1997|isbn=0-8006-2726-1|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=Encountering God: The Legacy of Lutheran Book of Worship|last=|first=|publisher=Kirk House Publishers|year=1998|isbn=1-886513-15-5|editor-last=Van Loon|editor-first=Ralph R.|location=|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=In the Context of Unity: A History of the Development of Lutheran Book of Worship|last=Quere|first=Ralph W.|publisher=Lutheran University Press|year=2003|isbn=1-932688-00-5|location=|pages=}}\n\n{{Lutheran Divine Service}}\n{{Lutheran hymnody}}\n\n[[Category:Lutheran hymnals]]\n[[Category:1978 books]]\n[[Category:Christian prayer books]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian texts]]\n[[Category:1978 in music]]\n[[Category:1978 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:Lutheran Church\u2013Missouri Synod]]\n[[Category:Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]\n", "name_user": "Shruti14", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lutheran_Book_of_Worship"}
{"title_page": "Lira (awards)", "text_new": "{{short description|Belarusian awards show}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name = [[Lira (awards)|Lira]]\n| original name = {{lang-be|\u041b\u0456\u0440\u0430}}\n| current_awards = \n| former name = The National Music Awards\n| description = musical awards\n| image = \n| imagesize = 220px\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| presenter = \n| sponsor = [[Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus|The Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus]]\n| country = [[Belarus]]\n| network = [[Capital TV (Belarus)|Capital TV]] (2011\u20132013)<br/>[[All-National TV]] (2014\u2013present)\n| year = {{start date|13|12|2011|1}}\n}}\nThe '''Lira''' ({{lang-be|\u041b\u0456\u0440\u0430}}) (until 2014, the National Music Awards ({{lang-be|\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u044f}})) is a national music award of [[Belarus]] in the field of popular music, founded on December 24, 2010, at the initiative of the [[Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus]].\n\nIn 1994, the predecessor of this award was {{lang-be|\u0417\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430\u044f \u043b\u0456\u0440\u0430}}.<ref name=\"\u0430\" /> Since 2011, it was carried out annually by the [[Capital TV (Belarus)|Capital TV]] channel, since 2014 it was conducted by the [[All-National TV]] channel every second year.\n== History ==\n=== Prehistory ===\nOn October 15, 2010, the chairman of the [[National State Television and Radio Company of Belarus]] [[Alexander Zimovsky]] announced that the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus had proposed the creation of the republican television contest \u201cNational Music Awards\u201d in December. The awards were to be presented in the nominations \u201cBest Song of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Performer,\u201d \u201cBest Band,\u201d \u201cOpening of the Year,\u201d and \u201cFor Contribution to the Development of Belarusian Pop Music.\u201d<ref>{{cite journal|author=|first=|date=2010-10-16|title=\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u044f\u00bb|url=http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=4821&mode=print|url-status=live|journal=[[Kultura (Belarusian newspaper)|Kultura]]|language=be|volume=|issue=42 (962)|pages=|issn=|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411065627/http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=4821&mode=print|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2010, the [[Council of Ministers of the Republic of Belarus]] adopted Decree #1885 \u201c{{lang-be|\u0410\u0431 \u0437\u0430\u0446\u0432\u044f\u0440\u0434\u0436\u044d\u043d\u043di \u041f\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0436\u044d\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0430\u0431 \u0440\u044d\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043bi\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043ai\u043c \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0435 \u201e\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043ci\u044f \u045e \u0433\u0430\u043bi\u043d\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0433\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0442\u0432\u0430\u201c}}.\u201d In paragraph #2 of the Regulation, the purpose of the competition was to promote the work of talented Belarusian pop singers, as well as composers, songwriters, sound engineers, arrangers, producers, and journalists. Clause #3 of the document determined the list of nominations for which the competition may be held: 3.1. nominations the winners in which are determined by the expert council taking into account the results of Internet and SMS voting (6): \u201cBest Song of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Performer,\u201d \u201cBest Collective of Performers,\u201d \u201cOpening of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Composer,\u201d and \u201cBest songwriter\u201d; 3.2. nominations whose winners are determined by the expert council (10): \u201cBest [[Belarusian language|Belarusian-language]] Song of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Music Album,\u201d \u201cBest Arrangement,\u201d \u201cBest Concert Program,\u201d \u201cBest Concert Abroad,\u201d \u201cBest Music Video of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Journalist,\u201d \u201cBest Sound Engineer,\u201d\u201c Best Producer,\u201d and \u201cFor Contribution to the Development of Belarusian Pop Music.\u201d According to paragraph #4, \u201cthe competition is held annually from January to December\u201d and \u201cthe winners of the competition are determined by the results of their activities for the current year.\u201d In addition, \u201cthe results of the competition are announced in December.\u201d According to paragraph #6, \u201cthe organizers of the competition are the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus and [[Capital TV (Belarus)|CJSC \u201eCapital Television,\u201c]] which provide \u201cpreparation and broadcasting of the gala concert.\u201d So, \u201cthe production of a television version of the gala concert, the announcement, and informational support of the contest\u201d as well as \u201cthe creation of information and advertising clips, their airing on television and radio\u201d are carried out by [[Capital TV (Belarus)|CJSC \u201eCapital Television\u201c]] single-handedly. \n\nAccording to paragraph #7, \u201cthe composition of the organizing committee is approved by the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus in coordination with [[Capital TV (Belarus)|CJSC \u201eCapital Television.\u201c]]\u201d In paragraph #8, it was noted that the organizing committee \u201cdetermines the nominations for which the competition is held\u201d and \u201capproves the composition of the selection committee, expert council, and counting commission.\u201d According to Chapter #3 of the Regulation, the competition is held in 3 stages. In nominations provided for interactive voting on the air of radio broadcasting and on the websites of radio stations, the selection at the first stage is carried out based on the results of such a vote. The selection committee determines 3 contestants for each nomination at the first stage, among which the expert council selects the winner at the second stage. At the final third stage, the counting commission sums up the points of the expert council based on the results of the interactive voting during the gala concert of the contestants in the nominations with such a vote. According to paragraph #26, \u201cthe winner in the nomination \u201eBest Song of the Year\u201c receives a cash prize of 95 basic units ([[BYR]] 3.325 million; $1111) and a certificate for creating a music video. The performer and songwriters are awarded in the nomination.\u201d In other categories with interactive voting, awards equal 77 basic units (BU). According to paragraph #27, \u201cthe winner in the nomination \u201eBest Belarusian-language Song of the Year\u201c receives a cash prize of 73 basic units ([[BYR]] 2.555 million; $853). The award in the nomination \u201cFor Contribution to the Development of Belarusian Pop Music\u201d was 70 BU, the awards in other nominations were 62 BV each. In addition, the award for \u201cBest Music Album\u201d is shared by the performer and producer, and for \u201cBest Music Video of the Year\u201d by the screenwriter, director, cameraman, and editor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pravo.by/document/?guid=2012&oldDoc=2011-3/2011-3(027-037).pdf|title=\u041f\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u043c\u0456\u043d\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u045e \u0420\u044d\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0456 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044c \u0430\u0434 24 \u0441\u043d\u0435\u0436\u043d\u044f 2010 \u0433. \u2116 1885 \u00ab\u0410\u0431 \u0437\u0430\u0446\u044c\u0432\u044f\u0440\u0434\u0436\u044d\u043d\u043d\u0456 \u041f\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0436\u044d\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0430\u0431 \u0440\u044d\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0456\u043c \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0435 \u00ab\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u044f \u045e \u0433\u0430\u043b\u0456\u043d\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0433\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0442\u0432\u0430\u00bb|last=\u0421\u0456\u0434\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0456|first=\u0421\u044f\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439|authorlink=Sergei Sidorsky|date=2010-01-29|website=|publisher=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u0442-\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043b \u0420\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u044c|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411125835/http://pravo.by/document/?guid=2012&oldDoc=2011-3%2F2011-3%28027-037%29.pdf|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|\u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0446=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430\u0446\u044b\u0456=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0443=}}</ref>\n\n=== Lira 2011 ===\nOn April 1, 2011, Michail Kazlovi\u010d, the head of the Arts Department of the Ministry of Culture of the Republic of Belarus, specified that the grade at the end of the year the gala concert would be estimated at 50% by the opinions of a professional jury and 50% by viewer'''\u2019'''s voting results.<ref>{{cite journal|author=\u0411\u0443\u043d\u0446\u044d\u0432\u0456\u0447|first=\u041d\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0435\u044f|date=2011-04-02|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u044f: \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u044d\u043f\u0446\u044b\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0443|url=http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=5550&mode=print|url-status=live|journal=[[Kultura (Belarusian newspaper)|Kultura]]|language=be|publisher=|volume=|issue=14 (985)|pages=|issn=|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411130450/http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=5550&mode=print|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|via=|\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0456=|\u0442\u044b\u043f=}}</ref> On November 1, 2011, the 1st Deputy Minister of Culture of the Republic of Belarus Uladzimier Kara\u010de\u016dski announced that applications for participation in the competition should be sent starting from November 15 to the Youth Variety Theater. Kara\u010de\u016dski announced that viewers would be able to vote for artists who compete for 5 of the 16 awards. The following nominations were determined for 2011: \u201cBest Belarusian-language Song of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Song of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Female Singing,\u201d \u201cBest Male Singing,\u201d \u201cBest Music Group,\u201d \u201cDiscovery of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Author of Music,\u201d \u201cBest Author of Lyrics,\u201d \u201cFor Contribution to the Development of the Belarusian Pop Music,\u201d \u201cBest Album of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Concert of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Music Video of the Year,\u201d \u201cBest Journalist (Music Critic),\u201d \u201cBest Producer,\u201d \u201cBest Tour,\" and \u201cStar of the Year (Best Young Performer).\u201d Sculptor Andrej Chaciano\u016dski designed the figurine to be presented to the winners, which incorporated the Belarusian ornament, a star, and [[sheet music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blr.belta.by/culture/view/natsyjanalnaja-muzychnaja-premija-prademanstrue-dasjagnenni-estradnaga-mastatstva-u.karacheuski-15957-2011|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u044f \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0434\u044d\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0435 \u0434\u0430\u0441\u044f\u0433\u043d\u0435\u043d\u044c\u043d\u0456 \u044d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043d\u0430\u0433\u0430 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0442\u0432\u0430 - \u0423.\u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0447\u044d\u045e\u0441\u043a\u0456|last=\u041f\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0443\u0448\u044d\u043d\u043a\u0430|first= \u0422\u0430\u0446\u0446\u044f\u043d\u0430 |date=2011-11-01|website=|publisher=[[Belarusian Telegraph Agency]]|language=be|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411130729/https://blr.belta.by/culture/view/natsyjanalnaja-muzychnaja-premija-prademanstrue-dasjagnenni-estradnaga-mastatstva-u.karacheuski-15957-2011|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|\u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0446=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430\u0446\u044b\u0456=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0443=}}</ref> Deputy General Director of [[Capital TV (Belarus)|Capital TV]] Paval Karanie\u016dski said that composer Ja\u016dhien Aliejnik wrote music for the presentation of the awards, which combines classic, pop, and folk styles. Karanie\u016dski admitted that applications from Belarusian performers from abroad were going to be accepted for the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blr.belta.by/culture/view/gala-kantsert-natsyjanalnaj-muzychnaj-premii-spaluchyts-use-napramki-suchasnaj-estrady-15979-2011|title=\u0413\u0430\u043b\u0430-\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0446\u044d\u0440\u0442 \u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u0456 \u0441\u043f\u0430\u043b\u0443\u0447\u044b\u0446\u044c \u0443\u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043a\u0456 \u0441\u0443\u0447\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0430\u0439 \u044d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0434\u044b|last=\u041f\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0443\u0448\u044d\u043d\u043a\u0430|first= \u0422\u0430\u0446\u0446\u044f\u043d\u0430 |date=2011-11-01|website=|publisher=[[Belarusian Telegraph Agency]]|language=be|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411131334/https://blr.belta.by/culture/view/gala-kantsert-natsyjanalnaj-muzychnaj-premii-spaluchyts-use-napramki-suchasnaj-estrady-15979-2011|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|\u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0446=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430\u0446\u044b\u0456=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0443=}}</ref> \n\nSongs written from December 2010 to November 2011 were accepted for consideration. The expert council included 100 people.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|author=|first=|date=2011-11-05|title=\u041f\u0430\u0437\u044b\u045e\u043d\u044b\u044f \u00ab\u041d\u041c\u041f\u00bb|url=http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=6596&mode=print|url-status=live|journal=[[Kultura (Belarusian newspaper)|Kultura]]|language=be|publisher=|volume=|issue=45 (1016)|pages=|issn=|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411131557/http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=6596&mode=print|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|via=|\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0456=|\u0433\u043e\u0434=|\u0442\u044b\u043f=}}</ref> The directors of the gala concert at the [[Palace of the Republic (Minsk)|Palace of the Republic]] determined on December 13 were Via\u010dasla\u016d Panin and Aliaksandar Vavila\u016d. Tickets for the show ranged from [[BYR]] 20 to 50 thousand ($2.4\u2014$5.9).<ref name=\":0\" /> On December 1, 2011, the head of the [[Capital TV (Belarus)|Capital TV]] production center Nasta\u015bsia Huzie\u013a-Hudzijeva announced that the voting for the \u201cPeople'''\u2019'''s Choice Award\u201d had begun on the channel'''\u2019'''s website.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=\u0411\u0443\u043d\u0446\u044d\u0432\u0456\u0447|first=\u041d\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0435\u044f|date=2011-12-03|title=\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f: \u0430 \u0432\u044b \u0430\u0434\u0434\u0430\u043b\u0456 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0441?|url=http://www.kimpress.by/index.phtml?page=2&DomainName=cult&id=6727?print|url-status=live|journal=[[Kultura (Belarusian newspaper)|Kultura]]|language=be|volume=|issue=49 (1020)|pages=|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20200410160645/http://www.kimpress.by/index.phtml?page=2&DomainName=cult&id=6727%3Fprint|archivedate=2020-04-10|accessdate=2020-04-10|via=|website=}}</ref> The expert council was headed by {{Interlanguage link multi|Anatoly Yarmolenko|ru|\u042f\u0440\u043c\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e, \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0439 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}. The competition received 545 applications.<ref>{{cite journal|author=\u041c\u0443\u0448\u044b\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|first=\u0422\u0430\u0446\u0446\u044f\u043d\u0430|date=2012-01-01|year=2012|title=\u00ab\u0410 \u0434\u0437\u0435 \u043c\u043d\u0435 \u045e\u0437\u044f\u0446\u044c \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0443\u044e \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e?..\u00bb|url=http://kimpress.by/?DomainName=mast&id=881&mode=print&page=2|url-status=live|journal=[[Mastatstva]]|language=be|publisher=|volume=|issue=1 (346)|pages=|issn=0208-2551|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411132528/http://kimpress.by/?DomainName=mast&id=881&mode=print&page=2|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|via=|\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0456=|\u0442\u044b\u043f=|\u0433\u043e\u0434=}}</ref> \n\nOn December 13, 2011, the winners became known:<ref>{{cite journal|author=\u0411\u0443\u043d\u0446\u044d\u0432\u0456\u0447|first=\u041d\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0435\u044f|date=2011-12-17|title=\u201c\u0417\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0430\u044f \u043a\u0430\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0446\u044b\u044f...\u201d \u0437 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043e\u043a\u0435, \u0430\u0431\u043e \u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u044f \u043f\u0430 \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0456\u0456... \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u044b\u0441\u0442\u0430\u045e?|url=http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=6771&mode=print|url-status=live|journal=[[Kultura (Belarusian newspaper)|Kultura]]|language=be|publisher=|volume=|issue=51 (1022)|pages=|issn=|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411133523/http://kimpress.by/?page=2&id=6771&mode=print|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|via=|\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0456=|\u0433\u043e\u0434=|\u0442\u044b\u043f=}}</ref>\n\n* \u00abBest Belarusian-language Song of the Year\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab{{lang-be|\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f \u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0430\u045e\u043a\u0430}}\u00bb (music by \u016cladzimier Kandrusievi\u010d, lyrics by Vo\u013aha Boldyrava, singing by [[Alyona Lanskaya]])\n*\u00abBest Song of the Year\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab{{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438}}\u00bb ([[Dmitry Koldun]])\n*\u00abBest Female Singing\u00bb \u2013 [[\u0410\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0430, \u0418\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430|\u0418\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0430]]\n*\u00abBest Male Singing\u00bb \u2013 [[\u0425\u043b\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0425\u043b\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432]]\n*\u00abBest Music Group\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab[[\u0422\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0446\u0430 (\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u0430)|\u0422\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0446\u0430]]\u00bb\n*\u00abDiscovery of the Year\u00bb \u2013 [[Teo (singer)|Teo]] \n*\u00abBest Author of Music\u00bb \u2013 \u041b\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0434 \u0428\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043d\n*\u00abBest Author of Lyrics\u00bb \u2013 \u041d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u043e\u0433\u0434\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\n*\u00abBest Album of the Year\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab[[\u0422\u043e\u043c \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439]]\u00bb ([[\u0425\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a, \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0435\u0432\u043d\u0430|\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0425\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u043a]] and band \u00ab[[S\u00b0unduk]]\u00bb)\n*\u00abBest Arrangement\u00bb \u2013 [[\u041d\u0435\u043c\u043e, \u0421\u0430\u0448\u0430|\u0421\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u041d\u0435\u043c\u043e]]\n*\u00abBest Concert of the Year\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab{{lang-ru|\u041b\u044e\u0431\u043e\u0432\u044c-\u0441\u0443\u0434\u044c\u0431\u0430}}\u00bb at the Sumer Amphitheatre in [[Vitebsk]] on May 4, 2011 ([[Yadviga Poplavskaya]] and [[Alexander Tikhanovich]])\n*\u00abBest Tour\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab{{lang-ru|\u042d\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0444\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0432\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u044b}}\u00bb (\u00ab[[J:\u041c\u043e\u0440\u0441]]\u00bb)\n*\u00abBest Music Video of the Year\u00bb \u2013 \u00abSee You in Vegas\u00bb (\u00ab[[Litesound]]\u00bb)\n*\u00abBest Journalist (Music Critic)\u00bb \u2013 Oleg Klimov ([[Sovetskaya Belorussiya \u2013 Belarus' Segodnya]])\n*\u00abBest Producer\u00bb \u2013 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0439\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 (band \u00ab[[\u0422\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0435\u0441 (\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u0430)|\u0422\u043e\u043f\u043b\u0435\u0441]]\u00bb)\n*\u00abFor Contribution to the Development of the Belarusian Pop Music\u00bb \u2013 [[Vladimir Mulyavin]] ([[VIA (music)|VIA]] \u00ab[[Pesniary]]\u00bb) <small>(posthumously)</small>\n*\u00abStar of the Year (Best Young Performer)\u00bb \u2013 [[Lidiya Zablotskaya|Lidiya Zablotskaya]]\n\nSpecial awards were given in the categories:\n\n* \u00abAuthor'''\u2019'''s Debut\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab[[\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442 (\u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u0430)|\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442]]\u00bb\n* \u00abBest Number Production (For a Vivid Stage Image)\u00bb \u2013 [[\u0412\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430 (\u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430)|\u0412\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430]]\n*\u00abBest Duo\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab{{lang-ru|\u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0442\u044b}}\u00bb ([[\u0413\u0430\u043b\u044b\u0433\u0438\u043d, \u0412\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|\u0412\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c \u0413\u0430\u043b\u044b\u0433\u0438\u043d]] \u0438 \u0418\u043b\u044c\u044f \u041c\u0438\u0442\u044c\u043a\u043e)\n*\u00abFor the Development of the Tradition of the Belarusian Song\u00bb \u2013 [[\u0424\u0438\u043d\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0433, \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u042f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|\u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b \u0424\u0438\u043d\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0433]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blr.belta.by/culture/view/nazvany-uladalniki-natsyjanalnaj-muzychnaj-premii-16030-2011|title=\u041d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044b \u045e\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0456 \u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u0447\u043d\u0430\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u044d\u043c\u0456\u0456|author=|first=|date=2011-12-14|website=|publisher=[[Belarusian Telegraph Agency]]|language=be|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200411133822/https://blr.belta.by/culture/view/nazvany-uladalniki-natsyjanalnaj-muzychnaj-premii-16030-2011|archivedate=2020-04-11|accessdate=2020-04-11|\u0432\u044b\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0446=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0456\u043a\u0430\u0446\u044b\u0456=|\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0443\u043f\u0443=}}</ref>\n*\u00abPeople'''\u2019'''s Choice Award\u00bb \u2013 \u00ab{{lang-ru|\u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0437}}\u00bb (music by [[\u041c\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0430\u043d, \u041e\u043b\