{"title_page": "Battle of G\u00f6llheim", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=February 2013}}\n{{one source|date=February 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{expand German|topic=|otherarticle=Schlacht bei G\u00f6llheim|date=February 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict|\nconflict=Battle of G\u00f6llheim|\ncampaign=|\nimage=[[File:Tod Adolf von Nassau.jpg|300px]]|\ncaption=Death of Adolf of Nassau, Simon Meister, 1829|\npartof=the fight for the rule over the [[Holy Roman Empire]]\n|date=2 July 1298\n|place=[[G\u00f6llheim]] near [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]\n|result=Habsburg victory\n|combatant1={{Coat of arms|Austria|text=[[Duchy of Austria]]}}<br />[[File:Blason Boheme.svg|20px]] [[Kingdom of Bohemia]]\n|combatant2=[[File:Arms of Nassau.svg|20px]] [[County of Nassau]]<br />{{Coat of arms|Electoral Palatinate}}\n|commander1=[[File:Counts of Habsburg Arms.svg|20px]] [[Albert I of Germany|Albert I of Habsburg]]\n|commander2=[[File:Nassau Arms.svg|20px]] [[Adolf of Germany|Adolf of Nassau]] \u2020\n|strength1=\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of G\u00f6llheim''' was fought on 2 July 1298 between the forces of duke [[Albert I of Habsburg]] and king [[Adolf of Germany]] over the prince electors' decision, without electoral act, to dethrone Adolf and proclaim Albrecht the new king. Adolf lost his life in the battle.<ref name=sue>{{cite web |url=http://www.suehnekreuz.de/rhein/goellheim.htm#text2 |title= Auf dem Hasenb\u00fchl verlor K\u00f6nig Adolph Krone und Leben  |publisher=Suehnekreuz | date=  | author= Fred Weinmann| accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref><ref name=\"Schneidm\u00fcllerWeinfurter2003\">{{cite book|author1=Bernd Schneidm\u00fcller|author2=Stefan Weinfurter|title=Die deutschen Herrscher des Mittelalters: historische Portraits von Heinrich I. bis Maximilian I. (919-1519)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DbytLiPcn4oC&pg=PA588|year=2003|publisher=C.H.Beck|isbn=978-3-406-50958-2|pages=360\u2013}}</ref><ref name=bio>{{cite web |url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz35116.html   |title= Adolf von Nassau  |publisher=Deutsche Biographie | date=  | author= Fred Weinmann| accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nAfter the death of [[Rudolph I]] at [[Germersheim]] on 15 July 1291, his son Albert I was to be the most suitable [[List of German monarchs|successor to the throne]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. However, Albert's undignified personality (ubiquitously called \"Albert the One-Eyed\", due to an open eye socket from a battle injury;) and his bad attitude dismayed the [[prince elector]]s. Mostly, though they feared too strong a kingship of the son of former king Rudolph I, who controlled one of the strongest domestic power bases in the empire. At the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Diet]] near [[Frankfurt]] the following year, they resolved to elect Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg, a cousin of one of the electors, a man with very little domestic power. Although Albert publicly recognized Adolf's election with good grace, he was driven by irreconcilable anger and plotted against him. Once king, Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg was determined to forge his own power base and attempted to seize [[Duchy of Thuringia|Thuringia]] and [[March of Meissen|Meissen]] from the [[House of Wettin|Wettins]]. As he had repeatedly abused his royal prerogative, Adolf was - without electoral process - declared banished by the electors. Adolf, however, defending his royal rights, went on campaign against the Austrian.<ref name=sue/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605015740/http://www.uni-bonn.de/~uzswac/marchetti-adolfvonnassau.pdf   |title= DIE ABSETZUNG VON K\u00d6NIG ADOLF VON NASSAU 1298  |publisher=Archive | date=  | author= Andreas Marchetti| accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref>\n\nAlbrecht had already followed the [[Archbishop of Mainz]]'s (one of the electors) request, to move to the Rhine and engage Adolf, who, however opposed Albrecht's troops with a strong army of his own. Prior to the decisive battle, near [[Ulm]] and [[Breisach]] Albrecht avoided the troops of Adolf, who intended to stop him marching west. Albrecht then advanced north through the [[Upper Rhine]] valley towards \u200b\u200b[[Mainz]]. Albrecht's army included contingents from the Habsburg territories, Hungary, Switzerland and those of Henry II, [[Prince-Bishopric of Constance|Prince-Bishop of Constance]], summoned at the fortified city of [[Alzey]] and seized the castle. Albrecht received the news of Adolf's deposition on June 23, 1298.<ref name=bio/>\n\nAdolf approached from \u200b\u200bthe imperial city of [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], in order to relieve Alzey Castle. His forces consisted of contingents from the [[Taunus]], Adolf's home region, the [[Electoral Palatinate]], [[Franconia]], [[Lower Bavaria]], [[Alsace]] and [[St. Gallen]].<ref name=\"Schneidm\u00fcllerWeinfurter2003\"/>\n\n==Battle==\n\nAlbrecht initially avoided a collision, but then on July 2, 1298 deployed his troops in a strategically favorable position on the ''Hasenb\u00fchl'', a hill near G\u00f6llheim. G\u00f6llheim community is located {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of Alzey between [[Kaiserslautern]] and Worms, near the ''Donnersberg'' massif.\n\nJohann Geissel describes the exact course of the battle in his 1835 monograph T''he Battle of Hasenb\u00fchl and the King's Cross at G\u00f6llheim''. The battle was fought in three engagements and lasted from the morning until the early afternoon. Accordingly, the battle remained undecided for many hours and, even after Adolf's death, did it not end immediately. The third engagement proved to be decisive. Adolf, who is said to have rushed to attack, was possibly slain by a [[Raugrave]] named Georg. Thereupon a large part of Adolf's army dissolved and fled, others continued to fight until they learnt about Adolf's death. According to Geissel's monograph, 3,000 battle horses perished on the losing side, while the winners fared not much better.\n<!-- reference?:\nOnce the battle had commenced, Albert rode his horse through the throng of fighting men until he had found Adolf. Earlier in the battle, Adolf had lost his [[helmet]], thus facing Albert bare-headed. It is said that they exchanged angry words, until Albert pierced his adversary through the chin. Adolf was thrown off his horse, and was butchered by his opponent. It is believed that Albert killed Adolf with a [[ballock-knife]], rising from the ground completely stained in Adolf's blood. \n\nAfter the gruesome battle, Albert was eventually elected King. His electors had good reason to be afraid of Albert, for he is often compared to the biblical King [[Rehoboam]], who often declared to his people, \"My father hath chastised you with whips, but I will chastise you with scorpions!\" -->\n\nThe result of the battle was generally considered as a judgment of God. Nevertheless, Albrecht insisted on a formal election by the electors, which took place in Frankfurt on July 27, 1298. As the kingship returned to the Habsburgs, the conflicts of interest between the electors and the king continued.<ref name=\"Schneidm\u00fcllerWeinfurter2003\"/><ref name=sue/> \n\nAdolf's widow, Imagina von Isenburg-Limburg, saw her husband's coffin transferred from Rosenthal Abbey to Speyer Cathedral by emperor Henry VII in 1309. There he was buried alongside his rival Albrecht, who had been murdered in 1308 by his own nephew Johann. Imagina had a memorial cross erected on the battlefield near G\u00f6llheim, which was designed in the early Gothic style. In the 19th century a chapel was built around it and has been preserved to this day.<ref name=bio/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kreuzstein.eu/html/body_goellheim.html  |title= K\u00f6nigskreuz |publisher=kreuzstein | date=  | author= | accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n* Wheatcroft, Andrew (1996) ''The Habsburgs'', Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-14-023634-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Battle of G\u00f6llheim}}\n\n{{coord|49|35|33|N|8|02|39|E|region:DE-RP_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle of Gollheim}}\n[[Category:1298 in Europe]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Holy Roman Empire|Gollheim]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Bohemia|Gollheim]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1298]]\n[[Category:Battles in Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{lead too short|date=February 2013}}\n{{one source|date=February 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=February 2013}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{expand German|topic=|otherarticle=Schlacht bei G\u00f6llheim|date=February 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict|\nconflict=Battle of G\u00f6llheim|\ncampaign=|\nimage=[[File:Tod Adolf von Nassau.jpg|300px]]|\ncaption=Death of Adolf of Nassau, Simon Meister, 1829|\npartof=the fight for the rule over the [[Holy Roman Empire]]\n|date=2 July 1298\n|place=[[G\u00f6llheim]] near [[Worms, Germany|Worms]]\n|result=Habsburg victory\n|combatant1={{Coat of arms|Austria|text=[[Duchy of Austria]]}}<br />[[File:Blason Boheme.svg|20px]] [[Kingdom of Bohemia]]\n|combatant2=[[File:Arms of Nassau.svg|20px]] [[County of Nassau]]<br />{{Coat of arms|Electoral Palatinate}}\n|commander1=[[File:Counts of Habsburg Arms.svg|20px]] [[Albert I of Germany|Albert I of Habsburg]]\n|commander2=[[File:Nassau Arms.svg|20px]] [[Adolf of Germany|Adolf of Nassau]] \u2020\n|strength1=\n|strength2=\n|casualties1=\n|casualties2=\n}}\n\nThe '''Battle of G\u00f6llheim''' was fought on 2 July 1298 between the forces of duke [[Albert I of Habsburg]] and king [[Adolf of Germany]] over the prince electors' decision, without electoral act, to dethrone Adolf and proclaim Albrecht the new king. Adolf lost his life in the battle.<ref name=sue>{{cite web |url=http://www.suehnekreuz.de/rhein/goellheim.htm#text2 |title= Auf dem Hasenb\u00fchl verlor K\u00f6nig Adolph Krone und Leben  |publisher=Suehnekreuz | date=  | author= Fred Weinmann| accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref><ref name=\"Schneidm\u00fcllerWeinfurter2003\">{{cite book|author1=Bernd Schneidm\u00fcller|author2=Stefan Weinfurter|title=Die deutschen Herrscher des Mittelalters: historische Portraits von Heinrich I. bis Maximilian I. (919-1519)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DbytLiPcn4oC&pg=PA588|year=2003|publisher=C.H.Beck|isbn=978-3-406-50958-2|pages=360\u2013}}</ref><ref name=bio>{{cite web |url=https://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz35116.html   |title= Adolf von Nassau  |publisher=Deutsche Biographie | date=  | author= Fred Weinmann| accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nAfter the death of [[Rudolph I]] at [[Germersheim]] on 15 July 1291, his son Albert I was to be the most suitable [[List of German monarchs|successor to the throne]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. However, Albert's undignified personality (ubiquitously called \"Albert the One-Eyed\", due to an open eye socket from a battle injury;) and his bad attitude dismayed the [[prince elector]]s. Mostly, though they feared too strong a kingship of the son of former king Rudolph I, who controlled one of the strongest domestic power bases in the empire. At the [[Imperial Diet (Holy Roman Empire)|Imperial Diet]] near [[Frankfurt]] the following year, they resolved to elect Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg, a cousin of one of the electors, a man with very little domestic power. Although Albert publicly recognized Adolf's election with good grace, he was driven by irreconcilable anger and plotted against him. Once king, Adolf of Nassau-Weilburg was determined to forge his own power base and attempted to seize [[Duchy of Thuringia|Thuringia]] and [[March of Meissen|Meissen]] from the [[House of Wettin|Wettins]]. As he had repeatedly abused his royal prerogative, Adolf was - without electoral process - declared banished by the electors. Adolf, however, defending his royal rights, went on campaign against the Austrian.<ref name=sue/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605015740/http://www.uni-bonn.de/~uzswac/marchetti-adolfvonnassau.pdf   |title= DIE ABSETZUNG VON K\u00d6NIG ADOLF VON NASSAU 1298  |publisher=Archive | date=  | author= Andreas Marchetti| accessdate= April 17, 2020  }}</ref>\n\nAlbrecht had already followed the [[Archbishop of Mainz]]'s (one of the electors) request, to move to the Rhine and engage Adolf, who, however opposed Albrecht's troops with a strong army of his own. Prior to the decisive battle, near [[Ulm]] and [[Breisach]] Albrecht avoided the troops of Adolf, who intended to stop him marching west. Albrecht then advanced north through the [[Upper Rhine]] valley towards \u200b\u200b[[Mainz]]. Albrecht's army included contingents from the Habsburg territories, Hungary, Switzerland and those of Henry II, [[Prince-Bishopric of Constance|Prince-Bishop of Constance]], summoned at the fortified city of [[Alzey]] and seized the castle. Albrecht received the news of Adolf's deposition on June 23, 1298.<ref name=bio/>\n\nAdolf approached from \u200b\u200bthe imperial city of [[Worms, Germany|Worms]], in order to relieve Alzey Castle. His forces consisted of contingents from the [[Taunus]], Adolf's home region, the [[Electoral Palatinate]], [[Franconia]], [[Lower Bavaria]], [[Alsace]] and [[St. Gallen]].<ref name=\"Schneidm\u00fcllerWeinfurter2003\"/>\n\n==Battle==\n\nAlbrecht initially avoided a collision, but then on July 2, 1298 deployed his troops in a strategically favorable position on the ''Hasenb\u00fchl'', a hill near G\u00f6llheim. G\u00f6llheim community is located {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of Alzey between [[Kaiserslautern]] and Worms, near the ''Donnersberg'' massif.\n\nJohann Geissel describes the exact course of the battle in his 1835 monograph T''he Battle of Hasenb\u00fchl and the King's Cross at G\u00f6llheim''. The battle was fought in three engagements and lasted from the morning until the early afternoon. Accordingly, the battle remained undecided for many hours and, even after Adolf's death, did it not end immediately. The third engagement proved to be decisive. Adolf, who is said to have rushed to attack, was possibly slain by a [[Raugrave]] named Georg. Thereupon a large part of Adolf's army dissolved and fled, others continued to fight until they learnt about Adolf's death. According to Geissel's monograph, 3,000 battle horses perished on the losing side, while the winners fared not much better.\n<!-- reference?:\nOnce the battle had commenced, Albert rode his horse through the throng of fighting men until he had found Adolf. Earlier in the battle, Adolf had lost his [[helmet]], thus facing Albert bare-headed. It is said that they exchanged angry words, until Albert pierced his adversary through the chin. Adolf was thrown off his horse, and was butchered by his opponent. It is believed that Albert killed Adolf with a [[ballock-knife]], rising from the ground completely stained in Adolf's blood. \n\nAfter the gruesome battle, Albert was eventually elected King. His electors had good reason to be afraid of Albert, for he is often compared to the biblical King [[Rehoboam]], who often declared to his people, \"My father hath chastised you with whips, but I will chastise you with scorpions!\" -->\n\nThe result of the battle was generally considered as a judgment of God. Nevertheless, Albrecht insisted on a formal election by the electors, which took place in Frankfurt on July 27, 1298. As the kingship returned to the Habsburgs, the conflicts of interest between the electors and the king continued.<ref name=\"Schneidm\u00fcllerWeinfurter2003\"/><ref name=sue/> \n\nAdolf's widow, Imagina von Isenburg-Limburg, saw her husband's coffin transferred from Rosenthal Abbey to Speyer Cathedral by emperor Henry VII in 1309. There he was buried alongside his rival Albrecht, who had been murdered in 1308 by his own nephew Johann. Imagina had a memorial cross erected on the battlefield near G\u00f6llheim, which was designed in the early Gothic style. In the 19th century a chapel was built around it and has been preserved to this day.<ref name=bio/>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n* Wheatcroft, Andrew (1996) ''The Habsburgs'', Penguin Books. {{ISBN|0-14-023634-1}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Battle of G\u00f6llheim}}\n\n{{coord|49|35|33|N|8|02|39|E|region:DE-RP_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle of Gollheim}}\n[[Category:1298 in Europe]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Holy Roman Empire|Gollheim]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Bohemia|Gollheim]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1298]]\n[[Category:Battles in Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n", "name_user": "Wikirictor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBattle", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_G%C3%B6llheim"}
{"title_page": "Ptychadena cooperi", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| status = LC | status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= \nIUCN SSC Amphibian Specialist Group|title= ''Ptychadena cooperi'' |year= 2013|page= e.T58498A18399600 |accessdate= 17 April 2020}}</ref>\n| taxon = Ptychadena cooperi\n| authority = (Parker, 1930)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\n'''''Ptychadena cooperi''''' is a species of [[frog]] in the family [[Ptychadenidae]].\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Ethiopia]].\n\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]], subtropical or tropical high-altitude [[grassland]], [[river]]s, intermittent rivers, freshwater [[marsh]]es, intermittent freshwater marshes, pastureland, rural gardens, [[urban area]]s, and seasonally flooded agricultural land.\nIt is threatened by [[habitat loss]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ptychadena}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2245908}}\n\n[[Category:Ptychadena]]\n[[Category:Amphibians of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Amphibians described in 1930]]\n\n\n{{amphibian-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| status = LC | status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= |title= '''' |year= 2016|page= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n| taxon = Ptychadena cooperi\n| authority = (Parker, 1930)\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\n'''''Ptychadena cooperi''''' is a species of [[frog]] in the family [[Ptychadenidae]].\nIt is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Ethiopia]].\n\nIts natural [[habitat]]s are subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]], subtropical or tropical high-altitude [[grassland]], [[river]]s, intermittent rivers, freshwater [[marsh]]es, intermittent freshwater marshes, pastureland, rural gardens, [[urban area]]s, and seasonally flooded agricultural land.\nIt is threatened by [[habitat loss]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Largen, M. 2004.  [https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/58498/all Ptychadena cooperi].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ]  Downloaded on 23 July 2007.\n{{Ptychadena}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2245908}}\n\n[[Category:Ptychadena]]\n[[Category:Amphibians of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n[[Category:Amphibians described in 1930]]\n\n\n{{amphibian-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "update IUCN citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ptychadena_cooperi"}
{"title_page": "Uroosa Qureshi", "text_new": "'''Uroosa Qureshi''' is a Pakistani television actress and model. She is best known for her roles in ''[[Meenu Ka Susral]]'', ''[[Daagh (drama)|Daagh]]'' and ''[[Sartaj Mera Tu Raaj Mera]]'' for which she was nominated for [[Hum Award for Best Soap Actress|Best Soap Actress]] at [[4th Hum Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hum Awards 2016 Complete Nominations List|url=http://www.brandsynario.com/hum-awards-2016-complete-nominations-list/|work=Maheen Nusrat|publisher=Brandsynario|date=April 6, 2016|accessdate=April 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hum Awards 2016 Complete Nominations List|url=http://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/112163-What-to-expect-at-the-Hum-Awards-2016|newspaper=[[The News International]]|date=April 13, 2016|accessdate=April 14, 2016}}</ref>  \n\n==Personal life==\nQureshi is married to actor Bilal Qureshi and they have a son. In 2017, Qureshi filed domestic violence case against him but the couple reconciled months later. Together they have a son Sohan.<ref>https://content.pk/pakistan/uroosa-qureshi-age-education-house-husband-children-family-dramas-contact-facebook-twitter-instagram</ref><ref>https://moviesplatter.com/actor/uroosa-qureshi</ref>\n\n==Television==\n\n* ''[[Meenu Ka Susral]]'', \n* ''[[Daagh (drama)|Daagh]]''\n* ''Kala Jadoo''\n* ''[[Sartaj Mera Tu Raaj Mera]]''\n* ''Piya Ka Ghar Pyara Lagay''\n* ''Sitara Jahan Ki Betiyaan''\n* [[Choti Choti Khushiyaan]]\n*Mohe Piya Rang Laaga\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n* [[Hum Award for Best Soap Actress]] - ''[[Sartaj Mera Tu Raaj Mera]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.tv.com.pk/celebrity/Uroosa-Qureshi/249/tvshows,page=1 Uroosa Qureshi] at [[TV.com]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCHq7AC6sRsOLmXvjeNHGg8g Uroosa Qureshi] at [[Youtube| Youtube Channel Official]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qureshi, Uroosa}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Karachi]]\n[[Cat